\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Commutative Algebra Homework 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given an example of a commutative ring (necessarily without identity) that
 does not have a maximal proper ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be any divisible group (for instance 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

).
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $A=nA$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{Z}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has no maximal proper subgroups.
 Indeed, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is a maximal proper subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 must have finite prime index in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (otherwise we can find a nonzero proper subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $B'\slash B$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\slash B$
\end_inset

 and pull this back to a proper subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

), say 
\begin_inset Formula $[A:B]=p$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A & =pA\\
 & \subseteq B\\
 & \subseteq A,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which forces 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

.
 This gives us a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we turn 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into a ring in a trivial way, namely we define multiplication on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\cdot a'=0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,a'\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly multiplication defined in this way gives 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 the structure of a commutative ring (but without an identity).
 Moroever since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has no maximal proper subgroups, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has no maximal ideals as a ring.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring with identity and let 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subset R$
\end_inset

 be a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}\,I$
\end_inset

 to be the radical of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(R)$
\end_inset

 to be the set of nilpotents of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}\,I$
\end_inset

 is contained in the intersection of all prime ideals that contain 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show the other containment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(R)$
\end_inset

 is the intersection of all prime ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{rad}\,I$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 be a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in I$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $I\subseteq\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 Since and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 were arbitrary, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}\,I$
\end_inset

 is contained in all prime ideals which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{rad}\,I$
\end_inset

 is contained in the intersection of all prime ideals which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Assume for a contradiction that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{rad}\,I\not\supseteq\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{p}\,\text{prime}\\
\mathfrak{p}\supseteq I
}
}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset

Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\supseteq I}\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathrm{rad}\,I$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 for all prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}$
\end_inset

 which contain 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\notin I$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We will find a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 but does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, which will give us a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the ring obtained by localizing 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 at the multiplicative set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x^{n}\mid n\in\mathbb{N}\}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{x}=\{a/x^{n}\mid a\in\mathbb{R}\text{ and }n\in\mathbb{N}\},
\]

\end_inset

and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\colon R\to R_{x}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding localization map, given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(a)=a/1
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x}=\rho(I)R_{x}$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, there exists a prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 but does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho^{-1}(\mathfrak{q})$
\end_inset

 contained 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}$
\end_inset

 would contain a unit, namely 
\begin_inset Formula $x/1$
\end_inset

, and hence would not be prime.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 By parts 1 and 2, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{rad}\,I\not=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{p}\,\text{prime}\\
\mathfrak{p}\supseteq I
}
}\mathfrak{p}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\emph on
all 
\emph default
ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{N}(R)=\mathrm{rad}\,\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{N}(R)=\bigcap_{\mathfrak{p}\,\text{prime}}\mathfrak{p}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a commutative ring with identity.
 Denote the Jacobson radical of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{J}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{J}(R)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $1+ax$
\end_inset

 is a unit for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{J}(R)$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $1+ax$
\end_inset

 is not a unit for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $1+ax$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{J}(R)$
\end_inset

, we see that in particular 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $1+ax$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ax$
\end_inset

 belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

, their difference also belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $1\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus our original assumption was wrong, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $1+ax$
\end_inset

 is a unit for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $1+ax$
\end_inset

 is a unit for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin\mathrm{J}(R)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 which does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $Rx+\mathfrak{m}=R$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is maximal.
 Thus there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+y=1$
\end_inset

, or in other words,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-ax=y.
\]

\end_inset

By assumption, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{m}\,\text{maximal}}
}R_{\mathfrak{m}}.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, it has no zerodivisors.
 Thus all of the localization maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{\mathfrak{m}}\colon R\to R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 are injective.
 In fact, they are just inclusion maps since we are identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and its localizations 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 with subrings of the fraction field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\subseteq\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{m}\,\text{maximal}}
}R_{\mathfrak{m}}.
\]

\end_inset

For the reverse direction, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x/y\in R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 for all maximal ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 for any maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 must be a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

! Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is not a unit, then there would exist a maximal ideal which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 does not belong to 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 maximal ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, and this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x/y\in R$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have the reverse direction
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\supseteq\bigcap_{\substack{\mathfrak{m}\,\text{maximal}}
}R_{\mathfrak{m}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

